‚ÄùI'm Sara Fuller the 6-12 business teacher and K-12 librarian. This is my 11th year at SPS, while it's my 11th year in the classroom this is just my second year in the library. I received my bachelor's degree from Kansas State University and my master's degree in instructional technology as well as my library media specialist endorsement from Fort Hays State.

I'm married to my husband Jamey who farms and we have 3 daughters, Haylee, Myka, and Tenley. We enjoy attending K-State football games as well as doing things around the farm.

I love teaching at SPS because we are truly like a family and it's great to see us all work together.‚Äù

Superior Public Schools knows that the most important factor influencing students' success is the quality of teacher in the classroom.

We will be recognizing our wonderful teacher by recognizing the "Teacher of the Quarter" each quarter this year. We will accept nominations from peers, parents, students and community members.

The nomination forms are on our website, found under the Quicklinks section. Please fill one out and email it to Mr. Kobza at mkobza@superiorwildcats.org. Nominations are due by September 28, 2020. Our next winner will be recognized at our October Board meeting. #NebraskaWildcatNation

post_text:
Check out another #FridayStaffFeature! #NebraskaWildcatNation

‚ÄùCindy Adamson, reading specialist para for Kindergarten, 1st and 2nd grades.

Career experience: dental assistant, retired nurse, and now 2nd year at SPS.

I am married and have one daughter, Jodie, and three grandchildren. Evan and Sage belong to Jodie and Henry is my step-grandchild.

My hobbies include collecting and dressing up teddy bears, and writing poetry, and spoiling my three cats.

Fun facts: I grew up on a farm. We had 2,000 chickens most of the time as my Dad was a main supplier of eggs for many businesses in Superior and other towns. We also had about 40 cats!

I love teaching at SPS because it is a rewarding job and the staff has always been very nice from day one when I started. It is exciting to watch the kids learn.‚Äù

JUNIORS have the opportunity to take the PSAT Assessment on Wednesday, October 14.

The PSAT is the preliminary SAT, which is equivalent to our ACT. The PSAT is a national merit scholarship qualifying test.

It is good practice for the ACT. Students are tested over verbal reasoning, math reasoning, and writing. The cost is $17.00.

Interested students are asked to stop by the Guidance Office.
#NebraskaWildcatNation

JUNIORS will be taking the ASVAB Assessment in the Library during Periods 1-4 on Wednesday, September 23.

The Armed Services Vocational Aptitude Battery measures strengths, weaknesses, and potential for future success. The ASVAB also provides students with career information for various civilian and military occupations, and is an indicator for success in future endeavors, be it college, vocational school, or a military career.

Students are asked to report directly to the Library once they have arrived at school. Attendance and lunch count will be taken in the Library. Please bring something to read between tests; other homework and calculators are not allowed. #NebraskaWildcatNation

‚ÄùHello all!

I‚Äôm Mackenzie Trumble and I work as a Speech-Language Pathologist. I serve students at PALLS, the elementary, the middle school, and within the RISE program. This is the start of my 6th year as an SLP and my 4th year here at Superior.

My husband, Sean, and I live in Nelson and are expecting a baby girl in early September. I enjoy anything sports related (Go Jayhawks!), traveling, and spending time with my family and friends.

One thing I‚Äôm looking forward to doing at Superior this year is working with the PALLS program! This is my first year working with preschool students, so I‚Äôm very excited to learn something new! I‚Äôm also looking forward to implementing new writing strategies within 4th and 5th grade.

I‚Äôm so glad to start a new school year!‚Äù

10 Superior Elementary students qualified for the 2020 Presidential Award for Educational Excellence.

President‚Äôs Award for Educational Excellence (Gold Certificate)

Students must have a grade point average of 90% or higher for their 4th and 5th grade years and first semester of 6th grade. Additionally, students must have an 85% on a state or nationally normed reading or math test OR a recommendation from the classroom teacher that supports outstanding academic strengths in a student.

Congratulations! #NebraskaWildcatNation

post_text:
Children need good nutrition all year long. When school is out during the summer months, many children no longer have access to even one nutritious meal each day.

Summer Meal Programs help to fill in the gap. Research shows a lack of nutrition during the summer months may set up a cycle for poor performance once school begins. We must do all we can to ensure that children get nutritious food during the summer months so that they are ready to learn during the school year.

Superior Public Schools will be providing lunch Monday -Thursday from 11:30-12:30 starting June 1 through July 30th

Lunch is FREE to anyone ages 1-18.

All lunches will be picked up by curbside at the Main Entrance of the High School.

Please contact the school if you have not completed the survey and would like to receive lunch. 402-879-3257 ext. 275
#NebraskaWildcatNation

Superior Public Schools is planning on conducting a driver's education class through the Nebraska Safety Center during the month of July. The class will be held July 6th through the 10th from 8:00 a.m. to 12:30 p.m.

We are hoping to have the class presented in person, but if this is unable to occur due to directed health measures that may still be in place, the students will have the option of taking the class online and completing the driving portion at a later date.

Students must be present for all days of instruction. Registration information and sign up for the class may be found and completed at the following website:

https://www.unk.edu/offices/safety_center/driver-education.php

Please make sure you scroll down to the Superior Driver's Education sign up towards the bottom of the page. If you have any questions, please contact Bob Cook at the High School from 8:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m. Monday thru Thursday and 8:00 a.m. to 3:00 on Friday at the following number: (402) 879-3257 ext. 116.

post_text:
Superior High School is planning on honoring the Senior class of 2020 during the May 29th cruise night.

The Seniors will be sitting on lawn chairs 6 feet apart in front of the businesses on Central Avenue from 7:00 to 8:00 p.m. Please show your support for these remarkable individuals by honking, waving, making signs to recognize them, or anything else that is in compliance with the directed health measures that are in effect.

We would ask individuals not to get out of their cars or approach the seniors as they sit on the sidewalk. We will also be turning on the football field lights at 8:20 (2020 in military time) and leaving them on for 39 minutes. One minute for each Senior in the class of 2020.

Let's show our support for the Class of 2020 as they continue to wait for their formal graduation ceremony. #NebraskaWildcatNation

Huge shoutout to the #NebraskaWildcatNation teaching staff during National Teacher Appreciation Week! We greatly appreciate all of your hard work and dedication.

Thank you Mrs. Jenny Utecht, Ms. Moore, Mrs. Baird, Mrs. West, Mrs. Ohmsted, Mrs. Kile, Mrs. Scheele, Mrs. Henry, Ms. Hollingshead, Mrs. Kuhlmann, Mr. Walz, Mrs. Beavers, Mrs. Hansen, and Ms. Scott. These teachers go above and beyond when it comes to working with our elementary students.

Mrs. Mueller, Ms. Arickxx, Mrs. Blevins, Mrs. Schuster, Mrs. Rempe, Mr. Going, Mr. Haley, Mr. Miller, Mrs. Fuller, Mr. Hershberger, Ms. Jameson, Mrs. Ehlers, and Mrs. Dayna Miller we appreciate you. Thanks for all of the hard work you put in with our junior/senior high students.

(We know this isn't quite everyone we have on our teaching staff, but some of them are fortunate enough to have their own special recognition day/week.)
#NebraskaWildcatNation

post_text:
Parents...are you wanting to monitor what your students are doing on their school Chromebooks? Our monitoring system now offers an app for parents. Some of the features include: viewing their top 5 websites, seeing if their teacher has had to close tabs, see the number of times they've reached a blocked page, and lots more. You can see all of the features at www.goguardian.com/parent-app/

If you would like to sign up for this you will have to email techhelp@superiorwildcats.org and please include your child's name. We will then send an email back to you with log-in information.

Download the Apple App here: https://apps.apple.com/us/app/goguardian-parent-app/id1470168511

Download the Android App here: https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.goguardian.parent&hl=en_US

shared_text:
Nebraska Department of Health and Human Services
March 26 at 11:43 AM ¬∑

Social distancing means putting distance between yourself and others. Staying home and staying away from groups of people will slow the spread of the virus and save lives.

Everyone can help reduce the spread of #COVID19 and other respiratory infections by doing the following:

‚û°Ô∏è Avoid close contact with sick people and stay home if you are sick.
‚û°Ô∏è Wash hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds. If soap and water aren't available, use an alcohol-based sanitizer.
‚û°Ô∏è Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth with unwashed hands.
‚û°Ô∏è Cover your nose and mouth with a tissue when you cough or sneeze then throw the tissue in the trash.
‚û°Ô∏è Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces.

We all have a responsibility to protect our loved ones, and others' loved ones. Learn more about how to #KeepNebraskaFlat at the DHHS website: http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Coronavirus.aspx

Every Thursday morning, the Elementary students celebrate ‚ÄúThrowback Thursday‚Äú and greet various staff members throughout the building with a hug, high-five, or smile.

We‚Äôre going to continue this tradition with a new version of Throwback Thursday! Every Thursday beginning at 9:00 am, PK-12 staff members will drive through town, honking and waving to our students, whom we miss dearly!

Students are encouraged to get some fresh air and play outside in their yard, or stand on their front step, to wave back at us. If you have a message for us, make a sign!! We can‚Äôt wait to see you on THROWBACK THURSDAY!!! #NebraskaWildcatNation

post_text:
Fourth graders have been learning about how germs get into your body. Today they did a Quizlet Live to review what they‚Äôve learned. Here are some of the highlights:

- Wash your hands for 20 seconds.
- Fingernails are a common place for germs to be missed when hand washing.
- If you don‚Äôt have soap and water, use hand sanitizer.
- Keep your hands away from your face- germs enter primarily through the mouth, nose, and eyes.
- Hand sanitizer dries out bacteria and germs and kills it.
- If you don‚Äôt have a tissue, sneeze or cough into your arm covering your nose and mouth.

The Nebraska Safety Center will be conducting Driver's Education Classes at Superior Public Schools July 6th through July 10th if a total of 8 or more students register for the class.

A maximum of 24 students will be allowed on a first-come, first-served basis. Classes will run from 8:00 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. each day with a Student/Parent orientation taking place on July 6 at 8:00 a.m. On-street drive appointments will be scheduled with the instructor outside of class time.

Registration forms are below or may be picked up at the office during regular school hours. Please contact the school if you have any questions.

post_text:
The 2019 POST-GRADUATE SURVEY has been completed. The State of Nebraska, through their Rule 10 accreditation requirements, mandates that all schools conduct a Post-Graduate Survey every five years.

The purpose of the study is to identify good educational practices, determine areas for improvement, and to chart new directions for education. Surveys were recently emailed to the classes of 2014, 2015, and 2016; fourteen surveys were returned. Questions were asked regarding educational and employment activities since graduation, future goals, and recommendations for improvement.

The time and effort former SHS graduates expended completing this survey is notably appreciated. Suggestions will be shared with staff, administration, and the Board of Education, as SPS continues to provide a quality education for all students.

Please feel free to stop by the Guidance Office to view the results of the survey.
#NebraskaWildcatNation

PALLS preschool has been learning about community helpers this week. We had a great field trip to Peak Dental and the Post Office.

We also walked downtown to see some of the other local businesses and professions. Several parents sent pictures of what they do for work in the community, so the preschools could learn about those jobs as well. #NebraskaWildcatNation

post_text:
On Tuesday, February 11, 2020, during their regular monthly meeting, the Superior School Board voted to implement a middle school concept beginning with the 2020-2021 school year.

This would mean next year's 6th through 8th grade classes would make up the Superior Middle School. The process has begun to develop a schedule of classes for the middle school and will hopefully be completed in the next month or so.

With this being said, we will be having an informational Middle School Meeting for next year's 6th through 8th grade students and will post that date and send out a reminder as soon as the date is decided upon.

Please watch the school website and other social media websites for updates.
